		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailTitle" style="text-align:center;">
                            Summary on Grant Application Form</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailValue" style="padding:5px;">
                        <span id="lblAbstract">Nematic liquid crystal is a suspension of rod -shaped molecules in a liquid.The average direction of those molecules may be described by vectors of length one at every that minimise a certain energy functional. In existing liquid-crystal display technologies, each display cell supports just a single stable configuration of the molecules. To produce optical contrast, a voltage must be applied to re-orient the molecules. Voltage pulses must be applied continually in order for contrast to be maintained. Refreshing the pixels in this way consumes substantial power and limits the resolution of the display.A number of research groups world-wide are seeking to develop alternative technologies based on bi-stable liquid crystal cells. Bi-stable cells support two (or more) stable configurations with contrasting optical properties. Power is needed only to switch from one stable configuration to another. Successful implementation would lead to displays with higher resolution and requiring significantly less power than is currently possible, and would constitute a breakthrough in display technology.Orientation of the molecules on the boundary of the cell is determined by the coating used on the boundary and by chemical composition of nematic. Those can be chosen in such a way that on the boundary molecules will always be parallel to the boundary. In a confined cell with such boundaries, there are configurations of the molecules which cannot be continuously deformed into one another. This inequivalent configurations can be labelled by certain integer numbers. Energy of the nematic liquid crystal depend from the average direction and its rate of change at every point. Stable configurations of nematic are those which are local minima of the energy. One expects that there are many inequivalent stable configurations of nematic in a cell. Those stable configurations can be determined by solving a complicated system of nonlinear equations. describing configurations minimising certain energy.Our research will use recently developed powerful tool for solving certain special types of nonlinear equations, called integrability, to investigate inequivalent stable configurations of nematic liquid crystal and to determine their energies. This will allow to improve the design of bi-stabie liquid crystal cells.</span>
                        </td>
		</tr>
